Full Base Breeding Information- Condensed
Monster Rancher Metropolis: Monster Rancher 2 Archive (PSOne): Miscellaneous Q&A (Post New Questions Here): Full Base Breeding Information- Condensed
By Firefairy on Wednesday, September 6, 2006 - 07:15 am:

This is all the information I have determined I need for combining, both to decide what I want and to make sure I don't screw it up. ;-) It's easier to see what you're doing if it's all in one place, so I put it together.

*****

The "translated" lifespans and life stage info are the only parts that are my own work. The rest was gathered from various other sources. I got the base lifespans from the thread here, I think, and the stats and growth are from Kurasu's Combining FAQ. The full list of monsters is from her overall FAQ. The percentages used to figure the Life Stages are also from the thread here.

I am including even the ones I don't have information for so that it is known that, as far as I can tell, that information is simply not available at the moment. Might provide a base for the research types to know what's missing. I suppose they will crop up quickly, requiring updates, but we do the best we can. :-J

I am going to post this in two sections; it's wide enogugh to be cumbersome even this way; I'm not sure browsers would display it if I put it all up in one table.

It includes, in this order,

* Main Type
* Sub Type
* Descriptive Name
* Base Stats
* Base Stat Order
* Growth Patterns
* Total "Growth Points"
* Base Lifespan
* Base Lifespan in Years/Months/Weeks Form
* Lengths of Life Stages in Weeks
* Length of Both Primes Together
* Length of "Working Life"; Adolescence Through Early Elder

Note that the Main Type, Sub Type, and Descriptive Name are repeated at the beginning of the second portion for ease of use.

*****

There is an interesting feature on the life stages- not all of them are round numbers, and it has not been determined how the game handles this. All of the monsters with this effect have an even number of .5's, and their lifespans come out just as expected if you add the .5's together or round up half the time and down half the time.

The theories I can think of to explain this effect:

1: The game rounds up and down alternately. The key question is which it does first.

2a: The halves are added together, with the half-and-half week having characteristics midway between the stages.

2b: The halves are added together, with the half-and-half week having the characteristics of one or the other stage. Effectively the same as alternate rounding from the player's perspective, but possibly somehow relevant to the game.

3: The game rounds up and down in some more complex pattern. Could be almost anything.

For sanity's sake, I'm hoping it's not 3; it could take a very long time to figure out a more complex pattern.

*****

I include total "growth points" as a quick way to see the monster's overall learning skills. A monster with a higher number has fewer low-growth stats, which is good to know when trying to raise a stat-heavy breeder and because even one more point can mean a significant change in the amount of stats passed on in breeding.

Yes. It's kind of a pain. You figure out the pattern of base stats on the baby. Then you adjust the breeding stats (screen stat modified by growth pattern) of the parents into that same pattern. The more you match, the better the baby.

Quote:

and stat transfer is best when the chances of combining to get a particular monster is the least.



Never heard that one. I think that might be a hoax. According to what I've read, with personal experience corroborating, matching the stat position on all three monsters involved is the way to get max stat transfer. Doing it that way, I get an average of about 300-400 per stat if I match everything up and have really buff parents.

I highly recommend Kurasu's Combining FAQ if you are doing any careful breeding. You can get it at GameFAQs. Explains the whole thing in painstaking detail.
